VI heard about a high school in Chicago
p6
aVwhere students had to pass a certain number of courses to graduate,
p7
aVand if they didn't pass a course, they got the grade "Not Yet."
p8
aVAnd I thought that was fantastic,
p9
aVbecause if you get a failing grade, you think, I'm nothing, I'm nowhere.
p10
aVBut if you get the grade "Not Yet",
p11
aVyou understand that you're on a learning curve.
p12
aVIt gives you a path into the future.
p13
aa(lp14
V"Not Yet" also gave me insight
p15
aVinto a critical event early in my career,
p16
aVa real turning point.
p17
aVI wanted to see
p18
aVhow children coped with challenge and difficulty,
p19
aVso I gave 10-year-olds
p20
aVproblems that were slightly too hard for them.
p21
aVSome of them reacted in a shockingly positive way.
p22
aVThey said things like, "I love a challenge,"
p23
aVor, "You know, I was hoping this would be informative."
p24
aVThey understood that their abilities could be developed.
p25
aVThey had what I call a growth mindset.
p26
aVBut other students felt it was tragic, catastrophic.
p27
aVFrom their more fixed mindset perspective,
p28
aVtheir intelligence had been up for judgment,
p29
aVand they failed.
p30
aVInstead of luxuriating in the power of yet,
p31
aVthey were gripped in the tyranny of now.
p32
aa(lp33
VSo what do they do next?
p34
aVI'll tell you what they do next.
p35
aVIn one study, they told us they would probably cheat the next time
p36
aVinstead of studying more if they failed a test.
p37
aVIn another study, after a failure,
p38
aVthey looked for someone who did worse than they did
p39
aVso they could feel really good about themselves.
p40
aVAnd in study after study, they have run from difficulty.
