aa(lp55
VHow are we raising our children?
p56
aVAre we raising them for now instead of yet?
p57
aVAre we raising kids who are obsessed with getting As?
p58
aVAre we raising kids who don't know how to dream big dreams?
p59
aVTheir biggest goal is getting the next A, or the next test score?
p60
aVAnd are they carrying this need for constant validation with them
p61
aVinto their future lives?
p62
aVMaybe, because employers are coming to me and saying,
p63
aV"We have already raised a generation
p64
aVof young workers who can't get through the day
p65
aVwithout an award."
p66
aa(lp67
VSo what can we do?
p68
aVHow can we build that bridge to yet?
p69
aa(lp70
VHere are some things we can do.
p71
aVFirst of all, we can praise wisely,
p72
aVnot praising intelligence or talent.
p73
aVThat has failed.
p74
aVDon't do that anymore.
p75
aVBut praising the process that kids engage in,
p76
aVtheir effort, their strategies, their focus, their perseverance,
p77
aVtheir improvement.
p78
aVThis process praise creates kids who are hardy and resilient.
p79
aa(lp80
VThere are other ways to reward yet.
p81
aVWe recently teamed up with game scientists
p82
aVfrom the University of Washington
p83
aVto create a new online math game that rewarded yet.
p84
aVIn this game, students were rewarded for effort, strategy and progress.
p85
aVThe usual math game
p86
aVrewards you for getting answers right, right now,
p87
aVbut this game rewarded process.
p88
aVAnd we got more effort,
p89
aVmore strategies,
p90
aVmore engagement over longer periods of time,
p91
aVand more perseverance when they hit really, really hard problems.
p92
aa(lp93
VJust the words "yet" or "not yet," we're finding,
p94
aVgive kids greater confidence,
p95
aVgive them a path into the future that creates greater persistence.
p96
aVAnd we can actually change students' mindsets.
p97
aVIn one study, we taught them
p98
aVthat every time they push out of their comfort zone
p99
aVto learn something new and difficult,
p100
aVthe neurons in their brain can form new, stronger connections,
p101
aVand over time, they can get smarter.
p102
aa(lp103
VLook what happened: In this study,
p104
aVstudents who were not taught this growth mindset
p105
aVcontinued to show declining grades over this difficult school transition,
p106
aVbut those who were taught this lesson showed a sharp rebound in their grades.
p107
aVWe have shown this now, this kind of improvement,
p108
aVwith thousands and thousands of kids, especially struggling students.
