VSo let's talk about equality.
p111
aVIn our country, there are groups of students
p112
aVwho chronically underperform,
p113
aVfor example, children in inner cities,
p114
aVor children on Native American reservations.
p115
aVAnd they've done so poorly for so long
p116
aVthat many people think it's inevitable.
p117
aVBut when educators create growth mindset classrooms
p118
aVsteeped in yet,
p119
aVequality happens.
p120
aVAnd here are just a few examples.
p121
aVIn one year, a kindergarten class in Harlem, New York
p122
aVscored in the 95th percentile
p123
aVon the national achievement test.
p124
aVMany of those kids could not hold a pencil
p125
aVwhen they arrived at school.
p126
aVIn one year,
p127
aVfourth-grade students in the South Bronx, way behind,
p128
aVbecame the number one fourth-grade class in the state of New York
p129
aVon the state math test.
p130
aVIn a year, to a year and a half,
p131
aVNative American students in a school on a reservation
p132
aVwent from the bottom of their district to the top,
